<TEXT>
louis lamour whose old west novels about 
gunfighters lawmen and drifters drew on his colorful past as a 
gold prospector roustabout and jackofalltrades died friday of 
lung cancer he was 80 
he wrote 101 books nearly all of them westerns including 
hondohow the west was won the iron marshal the 
quick and the dead sacketts land and ride the dark 
trail 
nearly 200 million copies of lamours books were printed his 
works were translated into 20 languages according to his 
publisher bantam books 
lamour left home in jamestown nd when he was 15 working as 
prize fighter deckhand longshoreman lumberjack gold prospector 
coal miner circus roustabout fruit picker elephant handler and 
amateur archaeologist 
he became a prolific contributor in the 1940s and 1950s to pulp 
magazines and his first novel hondo was published in 1953 it 
was followed by 85 more along with 14 short story collections and 
one nonfiction book 
in 1984 president reagan presented lamour with the 
presidential medal of freedom 
lamour is survived by his wife kathy and a son and daughter 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
robert bruce stewart retired purdue 
university treasurer and executive who administered billions of 
dollars in gi bill veterans benefits died friday in vero beach 
fla he was 92 
stewarts 36 years with purdue began in 1925 as its controller 
in 1945 he was named vice president and treasurer a post he held 
until his retirement in 1961 
after world war ii as administrator of veteran affairs advisory 
committee on vocational rehabilitation education and training 
stewart coordinated 145 billion in gi bill benefits for 8 
million veterans 
he successfully fought president harry s trumans request that 
the veterans administration examine all textbooks used by veterans 
to make sure they did not support communist doctrine 
born in duluth minn stewart graduated from the university of 
wisconsin earned his doctorate from butler university and taught 
in minnesota and wisconsin he was business manager of albion 
college before coming to purdue 
survivors include his wife mary simon stewart 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
josephine mardis branigin widow of 
former gov roger d branigin died saturday at age 80 
she was born feb 4 1908 in shelbyville and graduated cum 
laude from franklin college where she majored in mathematics and 
biology in 1929 
in 1929 she married branigin who served as indianas 42nd 
governor from 1965 to 1968 a retired lafayette attorney he died 
nov 19 1975 
she is survived by her son roger d branigin jr seven 
grandchildren and two greatgrandchildren 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bill clark a former schoolteacher who 
became one of maines most widely read newspaper columnists died 
sunday after a brief illness he was 74 
clarks columns for the editorial pages of guy gannett 
publishing co newspapers embraced traditional values often 
featuring the fictional town of cedar river and country characters 
dispensing folksy wisdom 
a native of schenectady ny clark graduated from colby 
college and obtained an education degree from new york state 
teachers college he taught in maine and new york state where he 
became a school principal in greenbush 
after serving with the navy during world war ii he built log 
cabins around lake george ny area and operated a sawmill before 
moving to kennebunkport 
he taught speech and composition at york high school and writing 
at the university of maine in portland 
his column logrolling first appeared in the fall of 1956 
he is survived by his wife the former elizabeth thompson and 
two sons 
</TEXT>
