<DOCNO> AP880613-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a drug widely used to treat adults with aids 
appears to dramatically reverse the devastating effects of the 
disease on the brains of children new research shows 
the aids virus frequently robs young victims of their ability to 
talk and walk and lowers their intelligence 
the latest research shows that the drug azt seems to bring back 
childrens speech as well as other functions controlled by the 
brain 
functional ability returned to normal in many kids said dr 
philip pizzo who directed the study at the national cancer 
institute 
his research was presented sunday at the opening of the fourth 
international conference on aids 
azt also known as zidovudine or retrovir is the only medicine 
routinely used to suppress the aids virus called hiv in adults 
it can slow the progression of acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
but does not cure it 
pizzos findings were made unexpectedly during the testing of a 
portable pump to administer the drug to children he found that 
among other changes the youngsters iq scores rose about 15 points 
after they got the medicine 
everybody who looks at this data has to get excited said 
dr daniel hoth of the us national institute of allergy and 
infectious diseases we are all nervous by small numbers of 
patients studied but the data itself is very exciting 
dr martin hirsch of massachusetts general hospital in boston 
also cautioned that the preliminary study did not include a 
comparison group 
its intriguing he said of the results i would have 
liked to have seen a control group who were not treated 
pizzo tested azt on 21 aidsinfected children who ranged in age 
from 14 months to 12 years about twothirds got the virus from 
blood products while the rest were infected by their mothers 
before birth 
pizzo said that 62 percent of the patients had suffered clear 
neurological damage from the virus and in every case they were 
improved after taking azt 
the iqs of those who had obvious brain impairment rose from 
about 70 to 85 among those who were judged to be mentally normal 
when the study began the iqs improved from about 95 to 105 
suggesting that they had probably already suffered subtle mental 
injury from the infection 
pizzo said the youngsters continued to improve steadily nine 
months after the treatment started 
brain scans also showed that missing tissue seemed to be 
restored in the infected youngsters brains pizzo speculated that 
cells that had been shrunken by the virus were restored to their 
normal size 
he cautioned that further study will be necessary to learn how 
long the improvement lasts and whether the children eventually 
worsen again 
in a separate study dr catherine wilfert of duke university 
medical center in durham nc described a preliminary threemonth 
study of the drugs safety in children 
she said the work shows that youngsters tolerate the treatment 
well and while its too soon to draw firm conclusions our 
feeling is that the number of opportunistic infections is 
substantially reduced 
research by dr maxime seligmann of hopital saintlouis in paris 
suggests that combining azt with the herpes drug acyclovir 
significantly improves its effectiveness in people with aids 
in four months of testing on 130 patients there were 25 deaths 
among patients who got azt alone compared with 11 among people who 
got both drugs 
these preliminary data suggest that acyclovir may have 
additional benefit without additional toxicity in patients with 
fullblown aids seligmann said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

