<DOCNO> AP880613-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the presidents guest house is meant to be fit 
for a king but when explosive gas leaked in and a chandelier 
crashed onto the bed where visiting heads of state sleep some work 
was clearly in order 
six years and 13 million later blair house is now a guest 
house worthy of this great nation says ambassador selwa 
roosevelt the chief of protocol who oversaw the restoration 
mikhail gorbachev couldnt stay there last december for his 
summit with president reagan because the house was closed for 
repairs but should he return this year he would find a new wing 
renovated kitchen plumbing fire and safety systems new 
electrical heating and air conditioning 
not a palace perhaps but not the dilapidated antique it was in 
june 1982 then the house was judged uninhabitable after gas leaked 
into the boiler room and a chandelier fell on the bed fortunately 
then unoccupied 
we all realized that the house was in very bad shape all you 
had to do was look at it says mrs roosevelt it had a veneer 
of looking all right because it had a certain warmth and all of 
that but the minute you started looking the rugs were threadbare 
the steps were sagging the plumbing was unbelievable the kitchens 
were like kitchens at the turn of the century 
blair house actually predates the turn of the century and it is 
an architectural gem rich in history it consists of four 
connecting buildings across from the white house on pennsylvania 
avenue and around the corner on jackson place 
the original house dates from 1824 and was long owned by francis 
preston blair a member of the powerful intimate group around 
president andrew jackson that was called the kitchen cabinet 
later the house was a meeting place for leaders on both sides 
of the conflict that became the civil war in a small room to the 
right of the front door col robert e lee was offered the command 
of the union armies and declined in favor of his native 
commonwealth of virginia 
president roosevelt approved the acquisition of the house in 
1942 saying the government needed it for the entertainment of 
distinguished visitors 
on nov 1 1950 an assassination attempt was made on president 
truman at blair house by two puerto rican nationalists who 
attempted to force their way in the attempt failed and one of the 
nationalists was killed leslie coffelt a white house guard died 
in preventing the assailants from gaining entrance and a plaque 
outside the house commemorates his heroism 
in more recent times columnist diana mclellan got into hot 
water in 1981 when writing her column for the washington post she 
carried an item that thenpresident carter had bugged blair 
house where presidentelect ronald reagan was staying before the 
inaugural the post retracted the item after carter threatened to 
sue for libel 
when the general services administration decided in 1982 that 
blair house was so dilapidated it was dangerous the agency said 
millions of dollars were needed to repair the structure 
the alternative was to tear it down there was nothing in 
between mrs roosevelt said 
congress appropriated 86 million and another 48 million was 
raised from private sources to pay for the project mrs roosevelt 
hopes to have more than 1 million left for a fund to maintain the 
house 
there has been little skimping in the refurbishing the 
collection of antiques has been expanded many of them donated 
along with china silver and fabrics the room where visiting heads 
of state receive the press is an uncommonly elegant pressroom with 
its two fireplaces blue damask upholstery red serabend rugs and 
view of the white house across pennsylvania avenue 
the state department sees the house as one of its diplomatic 
assets secretary of state george p shultz has said the feelings 
of being truly welcome which staying at the presidential guest 
house foster can tip the balance in our favor with many nations 
where personal relationships are vitally important 
when people feel welltreated and warmly treated this makes 
it much easier mrs roosevelt says 
she believes the american people can be proud of the house 
which she says is neither ostentatious nor plebian 
they dont want pretensions because the american people arent 
that way this house sort of straddles a very nice line its not 
too grand but it has elegance she says its really just the 
right degree of grandness 
</TEXT>
