<TEXT>
the fbi should include stringent safeguards 
against abuse in the guidelines it used to launch a lengthy 
investigation of reagan administration political opponents says a 
former justice department aide 
eric richard said the bureaus investigation of the committee in 
solidarity with the people in el salvador from 1983 to 1985 was 
carried out under relatively lenient guidelines on foreign 
counterintelligence and international terrorism the group opposes 
reagan administration policies in central america 
in prepared congressional testimony richard said the probe 
could justifiably have been conducted under another set of 
guidelines the relatively rigorous set of investigative rules 
governing domestic security and terrorism investigations 
details of the fbi investigation of cispes surfaced in february 
internal fbi documents showed that agents investigated nuns union 
members and college professors who opposed reagan administration 
central america policy photographing protesters at peace rallies 
and recording license plate numbers the investigation involved 
nearly all of the fbis field offices 
the more lenient foreign counterintelligence guidelines allowed 
the fbi to conduct a much broader investigation than would have 
been possible under the domestic investigation guidelines 
richard suggested that the fbi rework the international 
terrorism guidelines and apply some of the safeguards against abuse 
that are contained in the domestic security guidelines 
the international guidelines permit investigations of entire 
organizations under the domestic standards investigations must 
focus on participants who knowingly act to further criminal 
objectives 
the domestic guidelines also specify that before investigations 
are opened the danger to privacy and free expression posed by an 
investigation must be considered 
if these standards had been conscientiously applied to the 
cispes investigation it seems certain that an ongoing intrusion 
into legitimate political activity would have ended much sooner 
said richard 
richard the attorney generals special assistant for 
intelligence during the carter administration made his remarks in 
testimony to be delivered to the house subcommittee on civil and 
constitutional rights 
the investigation of cispes began march 30 1983 prompted by an 
informants claim that members were covertly furnishing money and 
supplies to the farabundo marti national liberation front a 
leftist group seeking to seize power in el salvador 
the probe was closed in june 1985 when the justice department 
concluded that the group was involved in political activities 
protected by the first amendment and was not participating in 
international terrorism 
</TEXT>
