democratic nomineetobe michael dukakis says as 
president he would wage a real war on drugs something he 
says the reagan administration has failed to do 
dukakis was focusing on drug issues today he had meetings set 
with leaders of his state antidrug program and with members of 
congress to discuss national efforts to fight drugs 
a day earlier dukakis was in utah to address the nations 
mayors and was harshly critical of the administrations dealings 
with panamas manuel antonio noriega who is under indictment on 
drug charges 
if elected dukakis told the us conference of mayors in salt 
lake city on sunday he would tell the cia and other agencies 
never again never again are you going to bankroll a drug peddler 
whos poisoning our society and killing our children 
dukakis also chided reagan for ignoring efforts by latin 
american leaders to get noriega to step down 
they tried to go it alone and they fell flat on their face 
dukakis said of administration efforts to oust noriega 
dukakis said he would direct more foreign aid to antidrug 
efforts including support for drugcrop eradication and step up 
protection of officials in drugproducing nations who have the 
guts to join us in this war 
he said the military should be prepared to assist those efforts 
dukakis outlined a domestic antidrug effort he said would 
include tougher drug laws and stiffer fines property seizures and 
sentences along with increased cooperation between federal state 
and local law enforcement agencies he called for expanded drug 
education for students and teachers and guaranteed access to drug 
treatment 
for us the stakes are clear dukakis said in a speech well 
received by the mayors a largely democratic group the war is 
on 
dukakis did not mention his certain republican challenger vice 
president george bush by name but he attacked administration 
antidrug efforts in which bush played a part when he headed an 
antidrug task force 
what we have today is chaos dukakis said of the 
administrations antidrug effort 
dukakis picked up endorsements from more than 500 democratic 
