<TEXT>
the supreme court declining to study an 
unprecedented racialdesegregation case today refused to free 
yonkers ny officials from having to integrate city schools and 
build subsidized housing to overcome decades of discrimination 
the court without comment left intact rulings that yonkers 
must build subsidized housing in predomimantly white sections of 
the city and create magnet schools to reduce segregation 
the case stemming from a justice department lawsuit begun by 
the carter administration eight years ago marked the first time 
the government linked discrimination in education and housing 
yonkers with some 200000 residents is located just north of 
new york city 
us district judge leonard b sand in a 600page decision in 
1985 ruled that yonkers officials intentionally and unlawfully 
promoted racial segregation through their housing and school 
policies 
he said the city had confined subsidized housing to 
predominantly black and hispanic southwest yonkers and that 
officials had bowed to the racial bias of some whites in resisting 
school integration 
the judge then ordered the city to pay the multimilliondollar 
bill for desegregating the school system and building 200 units of 
subsidized housing in predominantly white sections of the city 
city officials agreed last january to build the 200 units but 
then sought to cancel the courtapproved agreement sand refused on 
june 8 to cancel the agreement 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld sands 1985 ruling 
in a 163page decision last december 
the appeals court rejected arguments by school board and city 
officials that discrimination in schools and housing should not be 
linked 
when two actors have cooperated in a given venture each 
contributing to the outcome that each desires it requires no 
stretch of legal doctrine to conclude that each actor is liable if 
the result deliberately attained is unlawful the appeals court 
said 
the reagan administration supported the appeals court ruling 
urging the supreme court to reject the appeals acted on today 
as they have throughout this litigation the school board 
and the city blame each other for the segregated yonkers public 
school system justice department lawyers said this 
fingerpointing however should not divert this courts attention 
from the substantial evidence of cooperative intentionally 
segregative actions by both the board and the city 
the cases are yonkers board of education vs us 871632 and 
yonkers vs us 871686 
</TEXT>
