the supreme court today rejected the appeal of 
a dupont family fortune heir declared mentally incompetent after he 
lent 212000 to a group linked to political extremist lyndon 
larouche 
the court without comment let stand rulings that control of 
lewis dupont smiths 8 million estate properly was taken from him 
in 1985 under pennsylvanias guardianship law 
smiths appeal contended that his freedom of political 
expression and association had been violated 
smith 31 lives in chester county pa he is the son of e 
newbold and margaret dupont smith and is heir to a significant 
portion of the family fortune 
in 1985 smith had access to about 15 million in assets and 
marketable securities he also received substantial income from 
trusts 
smith lent 212000 in early 1985 to caucus distributions inc 
an affiliate of larouches organization 
learning of his intention to lend an additional 75000 to 
caucus distributions smiths family on april 11 1985 asked a 
judge to appoint a financial guardian for him 
after several hearings the judge ruled that lewis was 
incompetent within the meaning of pennsylvanias guardianship law 
because he was liable to dissipate his assets and become the 
victim of designing persons 
the judge appointed the wilmington trust co a financial 
institution as guardian of smiths estate 
smiths freespeech challenge to finding him incompetent because 
he contributed to larouches political efforts was rejected by the 
judge it is not that kind of case lewis first amendment 
freedoms remain intact and he may exercise them as foolishly as he 
wishes the judge said 
his ruling was upheld by a state appeals court we agree 
that smiths mental illness has resulted in producing a condition 
that has made him a victim of the larouche organization the 
appeals court said 
the pennsylvania supreme court refused to hear smiths appeal 
last jan 21 
the case is smith vs smith 871753 
