<TEXT>
a newspapers thwarted attempt to obtain the 
names and addresses of jurors who served in a muchpublicized new 
york murder trial failed to win supreme court review today 
the justices without comment turned away arguments by newsday 
that the public has a constitutional right of access to such 
information unless there exist specific reasons justifying secrecy 
the controversy stems from the 1984 trial in suffolk county 
ny of william patterson on charges of murdering his estranged 
wife frances 
mrs patterson was shot through a window of her home while 
watching television with her two children on june 29 1982 
during jury deliberations in pattersons trial a reporter for 
the long islandbased newspaper asked court officials for the 
jurors names and addresses the request was denied 
after pattersons trial ended in a mistrial due to a deadlocked 
jury newsday continued to seek the juror information 
the suffolk county commissioner of jurors refused to give the 
newspaper the information it sought he said the jurors names and 
addresses fell within the confidentiality exemptions of a state law 
aimed at curtailing secrecy within the state court system 
newsday sued over the blocked access claiming a constitutional 
right to criminal trial records 
three state courts rejected newsdays appeal 
the new york court of appeals the states highest court ruled 
last dec 23 that the names and addresses of jurors who serve in 
criminal trials may be kept confidential 
inasmuch as newsday has not contended that it has been 
denied access to any judicial proceedings or to any transcripts of 
any proceedings newsdays constitutional right of access has not 
been violated the state court ruled 
in the appeal acted on today newsday relied on past supreme 
court decisions upholding the publics right to attend criminal 
trials including jury selection and pretrial hearings 
the appeal said the interest which led this court to 
recognize such rights are also promoted by access to the names 
and addresses of jurors 
the newspaper urged the court to recognize a first amendment 
right of access to jurors names and addresses which must be 
properly considered before such access may be denied 
the case is newsday vs sise 871748 
