<TEXT>
the worlds most powerful atom smasher is 
set to start exploring some of natures deepest mysteries this week 
and physicists are thrilled at the prospects for scientific 
breakthroughs 
after nearly 10 years of construction and finetuning the giant 
collider at the fermi national accelerator laboratory in suburban 
batavia west of chicago is ready to come on line to smash protons 
and antiprotons together 
we have the potential for making more discoveries in 
highenergy physics than at any other time in history says fermi 
director leon lederman 
fermilab spokesman richard dease said today that the startup 
date is not certain but it is expected to be this week 
more than 200 physicists from around the world will be 
participating in the search for tiny subatomic particles that have 
so far eluded scientists trying to unravel the basic details of how 
the universe works 
fermilabs collider has three times the power of its closest 
competitor the cern collider in geneva switzerland and could 
open the door to new unexpected scientific discoveries officials 
say 
now we really get to go into the unknown says harvard 
physicist roy schwitters thats why were in the business 
schwitters codirector of the 40 million collider detector 
facility compared the collider to using wrecking bars and 
sledgehammers to try to find the treasure 
the fermilab collider whirls protons and antiprotons around in 
opposite directions on a 4mile circular track called the tevatron 
the protons and antiprotons travel at a speed close to that of 
light 186000 miles a second 
when they collide they annihilate in a burst of energy reaching 
2 trillion electron volts equivalent to a temperature of 10000 
trillion degrees 
the detector facility traps the traces of particles produced by 
the collisions 
