<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that police 
officers sometimes may chase a person who starts running at the 
sight of them even though they have no reason to suspect criminal 
conduct 
the court unanimously ruled that michigan prosecutors may use as 
evidence the drugs dropped by a man who began running when he 
spotted a police cruiser on a detroit street 
writing for the court justice harry a blackmun said the 
detroit officers pursuit of michael mose chesternut did not amount 
to a seizure under the constitutions fourth amendment 
the amendment generally requires police to have a warrant or 
probable cause to suspect a crime before conducting any search 
or seizure 
the court held in 1980 that a person is seized as opposed to 
arrested when in view of all of the circumstances surrounding 
the incident a reasonable person would have believed that he was 
not free to leave 
adhering to that principle blackmun said chesternut was not 
unlawfully seized during the initial police pursuit 
blackmun noted that the police did not sound their cruisers 
siren or order chesternut to halt they merely pursued him as he 
ran blackmun said 
while the very presence of a police car driving parallel to a 
running pedestrian could be somewhat intimidating this kind of 
police presence does not standing alone constitute a seizure 
he said 
according to court records chesternut was standing on a detroit 
street corner talking to another man a little after midnight on 
dec 19 1984 when he saw a police cruiser 
police said chesternut immediately started running away and was 
followed by the officers after turning a corner and as the 
cruiser drew alongside of him chesternut threw a number of packets 
to the ground and then stopped 
the officers said they picked up the packets which appeared to 
contain narcotics and then arrested chesternut he was charged 
with possessing heroin codeine and diazapan 
a state judge threw out the case ruling that police lacked a 
reasonable suspicion to pursue chesternut and therefore had seized 
the evidence unlawfully a state appeals court upheld the dismissal 
but todays ruling reinstated the charges against chesternut 
the case is michigan vs chesternut 861824 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

