<TEXT>
the supreme court today told wisconsins 
highest court to restudy the case of a teenager born out of 
wedlock who says she should be allowed to seek support payments 
from her fathers estate 
the justices said the wisconsin supreme court should review its 
ruling that a 4600 settlement between heather jo kruegers 
parents after she was born bars her from seeking any additional 
money 
todays order sending the case back to wisconsin said the state 
court should consider it in light of the justices decision last 
week striking down as unconstitutional a sixyear deadline 
pennsylvania imposed for filing paternity lawsuits 
miss krueger 18 of baraboo wis was born sept 7 1969 
her mother betty lou krueger reached an agreement in 1970 with 
arlen lee moore who admitted he was heathers father and agreed to 
pay 3600 in child support over the next four years plus 1000 in 
hospital costs 
a lawsuit was filed in behalf of the child in 1984 seeking 
additional support payments from moore who died in 1986 when the 
private plane he was piloting crashed 
moore owned his own biochemical research business his widow 
who lives in sun prairie wis is the heir to his estate 
the suit in behalf of heather jo sought 17 percent of moores 
gross income since 1974 plus additional money for his daughters 
medical bills and medical insurance the suit also sought to have 
her named his primary beneficiary in a life insurance policy 
the wisconsin supreme court last june threw out the suit the 
appeals court said the lump sum settlement between heather jos 
parents in 1970 bars any further lawsuit based on longstanding 
doctrine 
the state court said the doctrine is based on the principle that 
fairness to the defendant requires that at some point litigation 
over the particular controversy must come to an end 
the state court said the interests of heather jo were 
virtually represented by her mother when the agreement with 
moore was reached although the settlement agreement appears 
in hindsight to be low we are satisfied that it is not 
unconscionable 
the appeals court also rejected arguments that heather jos 
rights were violated because such lumpsum settlements were only 
permitted for illegitimate children 
wisconsin law was amended in 1981 to ban such settlements for 
children born out of wedlock and to require continuing support for 
them 
miss krueger is attending college at the university of 
wisconsinbaraboo center and is living with her mother who does 
parttime work as a cleaning lady and clerk 
wisconsin state officials urged the high court to hear the case 
and rule in favor of miss krueger 
attorney general donald j hanaway said permitting the lumpsum 
payments for those born out of wedlock creates a class of children 
totally deprived of an ability to receive child support from 
fathers who have the ability to pay 
the case is gerhardt vs moore 871103 
