<TEXT>
the supreme court ruling that the postal 
service is similar to a private business said today the service 
must pay interest on back pay owed to a worker who won a lawsuit 
charging it with illegal discrimination 
by a 53 vote the court ordered interest on back pay for a 
letter carrier in chesterfield mo who was fired and later 
ordered rehired 
justice harry a blackmun writing for the court said when the 
post office department was reorganized by congress in 1970 into the 
postal service it became in key respects more like a private 
enterprise than a government agency 
the reorganization launched the postal service into the 
commercial world specifically allowing it to sue and be sued 
blackmun said 
it follows that congress is presumed to have waived any 
otherwise existing immunity of the postal service from interest 
awards he said 
the court ordered interest paid to theodore j loeffler who was 
fired from his job as a letter carrier after 10 years 
his superiors said loeffler violated a rule dealing with the 
organizing of socalled boxholder mail that is sent to current 
occupant at an address and does not carry the residents name 
for a period in 1979 and 1980 letter carriers were not allowed 
to sort the boxholder mail in separate compartments of their 
carrying bags before beginning their routes they were required to 
leave the third class mail in bundles and sort it out at each point 
of delivery 
loeffler who worked in a rural area openly refused to obey the 
rule as did two female letter carriers 
one of the women was suspended and threatened with dismissal 
the other woman was warned but was not otherwise disciplined 
loeffler was fired when he was caught breaking the rule the 
fourth time 
he sued the postal service under a 1964 civil rights law banning 
sex discrimination in employment and a federal judge ruled in his 
favor loeffler was awarded 91871 in back pay and was ordered 
reinstated 
but the 8th us circuit court of appeals ruled that loeffler 
was not entitled to interest the back pay would have earned from 
the time he was fired until he won the suit 
such interest generally is authorized for those who win 
antidiscrimination suits under the 1964 act 
the appeals court said the postal service was immune from the 
interest payments because congress had not passed a law 
specifically eliminating the services protection against such 
civil rights suits 
the reagan administration said todays case could affect 
hundreds of employment discrimination cases pending against the 
postal service 
dissenting from the ruling were chief justice william h 
rehnquist and justices byron r white and sandra day oconnor 
justice anthony m kennedy did not take part in the ruling 
the case is loeffler vs frank 861431 
</TEXT>
