<TEXT>
an alaska delegation hoping to improve 
ussoviet relations and reunite eskimo families divided by the 
cold war took off today on a friendship flight to the siberian 
community of provideniya 
the flight aimed at cracking open a border closed for 40 years 
left nome at 1109 am adt for provideniya the federal aviation 
administration said 
dubbed friendship 1 the plane had left anchorage at 755 am 
for the 1hour flight to the western alaska town of nome the 
jumpingoff point for the second leg of the trip a 45minute 
flight to the soviet union 
the flight from nome to the eastern siberia port of provideniya 
is seen as a big step toward thawing relations between the 
neighboring regions once part of the same country before russia 
sold alaska to the united states in 1867 
eskimos once freely crossed the icy bering strait in motorboats 
and walrusskin umiaks to trade and visit with relatives the 
border was closed in 1948 amid growing cold war tensions 
this month the soviets approved todays onetime charter flight 
to provideniya after two years of work by alaskans promoting the 
idea 
eighty government officials eskimos and journalists were booked 
aboard the alaska airlines plane for the 225mile flight 
provideniya officials planned to entertain the oneday visitors 
with tours a banquet and a trip to an outlying native village 
the flight is long overdue says timothy gologergen 68 one of 
several siberian yupik eskimos who are making the trip 
this is the first chance to create peace towards our people 
and their people he said this way well have a chance to find 
out if the relatives are still alive there someplace and open up a 
little trade 
gologergen said his great grandfather migrated from siberia and 
kept in touch with relatives there until the iron curtain came 
down 
the friendship flight is part of a broader initiative that 
alaska business leaders educators and state officials have 
launched to improve relations with the soviet union those efforts 
combined with soviet leader mikhail gorbachevs policy of openness 
have started to chip away at longstanding barriers 
from a symbolic perspective the trip represents the reopening 
of an old gateway between alaska and the soviet union said gov 
steve cowper delegation leader im confident it will lead to 
better relations between our two countries for years 
the flight stems from the dream of james stimpfle a real estate 
agent in nome when alaskas oil recession began two years ago 
stimpfle brainstormed ways to improve the economy of his remote 
town of 3700 people 
he figured that if the alaskasiberia border were opened nome 
could become an economic and cultural center for both sides of the 
bering strait in addition to freer travel by residents stimpfle 
envisioned increased trade joint business ventures and tourist 
excursions by airplane and cruise ship between nome and siberia 
the barriers to such activity were and remain substantial 
though siberia and alaska lie only 3 miles apart at their closest 
point the regions are a world apart politically and economically 
even a telephone call from nome must be routed the opposite 
direction around the globe to reach provideniya 
officials in washington four time zones to the east and 
moscow 12 time zones to the west seemed content with the status 
quo 
so stimpfle tried some attentiongrabbing stunts he floated 
balloons from nome across the bering strait and pointed a huge 
peace sign in russian toward siberia 
he also wrote hundreds of letters to soviet and us officials 
urging the opening of the border slowly people began to listen 
especially after alaska airlines the largest air carrier serving 
alaska hopped on the friendship flight bandwagon 
it was only a short while ago that this flight was a dream 
said lou cancelmi alaska airlines spokesman i personally 
wondered if this day would ever come 
i dont think jim stimpfle ever thought for a moment that it 
wouldnt and thats what it takes to make something like this come 
true 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

