<TEXT>
george p shultz said proliferation is 
winning the race against disarmament and told the general 
assembly on monday that all nations should sign the nuclear 
nonproliferation treaty 
the us secretary of state said the danger of proliferation is 
most acute in south asia meaning india and its rival pakistan 
both have refused to sign the treaty and accuse each other of 
developing nuclear weapons 
he said that 136 nations have signed the 20yearold treaty and 
there is no good reason why every nation should not make such a 
commitment it is a contribution each and every state can make to a 
safer world 
shultz also said the united states is concerned about the 
introduction of advanced missiles into the persian gulf war 
because they have killed civilians 
hundreds of people were killed on both sides earlier this year 
when iran and iraq rained missiles on each others cities most of 
the weapons were believed to be scud missiles of an old soviet 
design some of them equipped with boosters for longer range 
shultz address to a special general assembly session on 
disarmament came a week after soviet foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze called on the united states to join a permament 
nuclear test ban shultz did not respond to a series of soviet 
proposals that won praise from many in the 159member assembly 
in his speech shultz outlined american achievements in arms 
control and said washingtons top priority in the field is 
concluding a ussoviet treaty to cut strategic nuclear arsenals 
by 50 percent 
does anyone doubt that the spread of nuclear weapons threatens 
regional and global security he said what state believes 
that if it now acquired nuclear weapons its rivals would not do 
the same 
now that the united states and the soviet union have agreed to 
reduce their nuclear arsenals it would be tragic for other 
countries to pursue the capability to cross the nuclear 
threshhold shultz said 
he said south asia is the area of greatest danger and urged 
countries in the region to take concrete steps to meet this 
urgent challenge the us is prepared to work with countries 
inside and outside the region to find a lasting solution to the 
danger of proliferation that satisfies all parties 
shultz was among the final few of more than 100 speakers who 
have addressed the general assembly since the special session began 
two weeks ago 
in his remarks about the iraniraq war which began in september 
1980 he said we already are seeing signs of a dangerous new 
arms race which will put at risk countries far removed from the 
gulf region itself 
use of the missiles and the killing of civilians makes a peace 
settlement more difficult he said 
the un session has been divided over key disarmament questions 
and diplomatic observers said it will be difficult to draft a final 
document which can satisfy most nations and be adopted by consensus 
the united states and western allies have called for limited 
pragmatic steps in arms control continued respect for nuclear 
deterrence a limited role for the un and recognition that 
bilateral arms talks must supersede multilateral efforts 
they say the treaty on intermediaterange nuclear weapons and 
some progress in ussoviet talks on 50percent cuts on strategic 
weapons show that bilateral efforts should be allowed to continue 
unencumbered by a multilateral apparatus 
western diplomats also have said that conventional disarmament 
is as important as nuclear disarmament and urged poor developing 
nations which clamor for nuclear disarmament to cut their own 
mounting expenditure in conventional armies 
after the speeches end tuesday or wednesday groups will begin 
drafting resolutions and a final document for this third special 
session on disarmament in 10 years 
but if the divisions are too great and the disarmament proposals 
too sweeping and utopian western nations are expected to demand a 
vote making consensus unlikely 
