newfoundland following an investigation by the canadian security 
intelligence service the royal canadian mounted police and us 
navy intelligence according to solicitor general james kelleher 
the minister declined to say if ratkai actually passed or tried 
to pass the documents to anyone but he said the offense involved a 
foreign agent he said that information would come out in court 
kelleher gave no details of the contents of the documents the 
canadian broadcasting corp in a television report said the papers 
involved operations at the us naval base at argentia 
newfoundland where us and canadian military forces cooperate in 
monitoring the movements of soviet submarines 
the solicitor general said no soviet diplomats or citizens 
residing in canada were involved to our knowledge 
but we believe the information the documents would be 
useful to the soviet union andor other east bloc countries 
kelleher said 
he said ratkai was not a member of the canadian armed forces or 
government but was believed to be a nativeborn canadian citizen 
he gave no other details on ratkais background 
ratkai was charged under a section of the official secrets act 
that prohibits the gathering or passing of classified documents or 
information that could be of use to a foreign power and could harm 
the interests of canada and its allies the offense carries a 
maximum penalty of 14 years in prison 
ratkai was arraigned in a st johns court on sunday and is 
scheduled to appear in court again on wednesday 
