along to jeffrey steefel who plays him in this show but without 
being dictatorial about it scardino says everybody else in 
the musical ill just give notes or suggestions with him i 
unconsciously start to act it out or show him and thats wrong he 
is the actor 
the original performers in godspell all came out of carnegie 
tech now carnegie mellon university they had been together for 
four years and had a strong background in an acting technique that 
involved story theater the telling of stories and the playing of 
games 
its a technique not taught much lately so scardino asked for 
and got an extra week of rehearsal to do theater games such as 
blindman trust exercises and circle games with the new actors 
they are exercises dedicated to creating an ensemble unit of actors 
and break down the social barriers 
its the only show in which you have to be deprogrammed when 
you leave it scardino laughs 
the director feels the musical will find a new audience today 
even though it has only been a decade since the show was last seen 
in new york plus get many of the people who saw it before 
im a 60s person the 40yearold scardino says we all 
thought we were searching for new definitions we thought we were 
revolutionaries either political or spiritual or whatever but 
there was a spiritual search alive and a rejection of material 
values or at least we thought so then we entered the 80s and 
weve come into yuppie materialism 
it was godspells naivete and honesty that attracted people 
in the 1970s scardino says adding that the musical had a fresh 
perspective on something that had lost meaning for people the 
gospel 
i think we are in a crisis of values now scardino says 
everybody seems to be involved now in another search for meaning 
or a new search for spiritual values its the pendulum swinging 
although it hasnt swung yet the kind of joy that godspell has 
the kind of hope that godspell gives that is needed and i think 
people will come and find it as refreshing as they did before 
