<TEXT>
here are some key dates in affairs of 
the north atlantic treaty organization since 1984 
june 1984 lord carrington takes over from joseph luns as nato 
secretarygeneral 
january 1985 us secretary of state george p shultz and 
soviet foreign minister andrei a gromyko meet in geneva and set 
the agenda for new superpower arms talks covering medium and 
longrange nuclear weapons as well as space and defensive weapons 
march 1985 mikhail s gorbachev is named general secretary of 
the soviet communist party and as such the leader of the soviet 
union nato defense ministers for the first time formally endorse 
the us strategic defense initiative or star wars plan 
may 1985 allied defense ministers approve the conventional 
defense improvements plan for strengthening nonnuclear forces 
november 1985 president reagan meets gorbachev for the first 
time in geneva 
january 1986 gorbachev calls for the global elimination of 
nuclear weapons by the end of the century 
march 1986 in a national referendum spaniards vote to stay in 
nato it is the first time a member country has considered leaving 
may 1986 nato foreign ministers meeting in halifax nova 
scotia urge bold new steps in eastwest negotiations to reduce 
troops and nonnuclear weaponry throughout europe 
october 1986 reagan and gorabachev meeting in reykjavik 
iceland agree in principle to eliminate all mediumrange nuclear 
missiles 
june 1987 nato foreign ministers endorse gorbachevs offer to 
widen the mediumrange missile deal to include shorterrange 
rockets later us gen bernard w rogers an opponent of the 
deal is dropped as supreme allied commander europe and replaced by 
gen john r galvin 
december 1987 reagan and gorbachev sign the missile treaty at 
their summit in washington west germanys manfred woerner is 
chosen to succeed carrington as nato secretary general when 
carrington leaves in june 1988 
march 1988 a nato summit meeting reaffirms the basic 
principles of the alliance pledges to modernize us nuclear 
weapons in western europe and calls for major reductions in 
nonnuclear forces 
june 1988 reagan and gorbachev meeting in moscow put the 
mediumrange nuclear missile treaty into effect 
</TEXT>
