<TEXT>
from an abandoned blimp base scientists are 
peering beyond the stars and studying how the earth moves 
their work guides ships at sea satellites in space and even a 
cab driver in chicago and could someday help predict earthquakes 
they also found that the generally stable miami area is rising a 
fraction of an inch a year 
on the grounds of the us naval observatorys richmond station 
south of here are optical and radio telescopes a visiting german 
laser system and soon a gravity meter all designed to pinpoint 
locations and distances 
were observing continental drift changes in the earths 
crust and movements along fault lines as well as the earths spin 
and wobble says alice babcock one of 10 civilians at the 
station and its director as far as i know this network is the 
only source of such measurements 
the station which costs less than 500000 a year to run is 
part of a nasa network used by the united states soviet union and 
other satellitelaunching nations to program guidance systems and 
pinpoint locations 
the data is being fed into a growing worldwide satellite network 
that will become the definitive source for navigators it is not 
only available to ships planes satellites and submarines but to 
motorists via computerized maps 
i met a chicago taxi driver who had a receiver mounted in his 
cab he said it was quicker and more accurate than using a map 
says ms babcock there are even handheld receivers can pinpoint 
location and headings for hikers explorers and rescue teams 
richmond set up in 1949 at a world war ii blimp base also has 
the only backup to the master clock at the us naval observatory 
in washington a basis for accurate time measurement all over the 
world the cesiumfueled clocks at richmond which measure time by 
the radioactive elements rate of decay are checked constantly 
against those in washington to prevent errors 
the exact time is shared with other points by bouncing the 
information off satellites even at the speed of light phone lines 
are useless for comparing the readings because switching stations 
can slow the signals 
however most of the staffs time is spent looking upward the 
60foot diameter radiotelescope seeks out quasars small sources of 
intense radio emissions billions of lightyears away at the edge of 
the visible universe 
if one of them seems to be moving we know its really the 
earth thats wobbling says ms babcock the measurements are 
constantly checked and rechecked to see how the earth and points on 
its surface are changing 
in addition researchers from the wettzell station in west 
germany are using a mobile laser telescope to fire green light 
beams at a twofoot orbiting lageos satellite covered with 40 
fourinch mirrors the beam bounces 3500 miles back to show up on 
a screen in a trailer crammed with electronic equipment 
you can do a lot of things with this information its a very 
accurate position fix for a satellite or for points on earth 
says german scientist walter etling distances over 1000 miles can 
be calculated to within an inch or two using this method he says 
the richmond scientists plan to install by years end a gravity 
meter a metal ball suspended in a magnetic field that can measure 
minute changes in mass below it and ms babcock hopes to install a 
laser system that can bounce beams off mirrors left on the lunar 
surface by us and soviet moonwalkers 
the new systems may eventually have to replace the observatorys 
optical telescope which will become as useless as washingtons 
when encroaching development lights up the night skies and makes 
stargazing impossible 
ms babcock has no doubt ever more exotic measuring sticks will 
be available in this field the technology is changing so fast 
we never really get to a standard system 
</TEXT>
