<TEXT>
foreign ministers of the 12nation european 
economic community on monday approved an accord establishing formal 
relations with the sovietled council for mutual economic 
assistance or comecon 
the agreement was initialled by eec and comecon officials last 
week in moscow it is to be put into force at an official signing 
ceremony in luxembourg on june 25 
the pact sets the stage for exchanges of information but doesnt 
establish bilateral trade relations 
it marks the communist blocs first official recognition of the 
eec since the common market was created 31 years ago for years 
moscow and its communist allies virtually ignored the eec calling 
it a quasimilitary extension of the americanled nato alliance 
the eec and comecon have been negotiating the terms of a joint 
declaration on mutual recognition since september 1985 
eec member nations include britain west germany france 
italy ireland luxembourg belgium netherlands denmark greece 
spain and portugal 
moscows partners in comecon are poland romania hungary 
bulgaria czechoslovakia east germany cuba vietnam and mongolia 
trade between eec and comecon members totaled about 50 billion 
last year about half of which was between the eec and the soviet 
union according to the june issue of eastwest publications a 
brusselsbased newsletter 
the eec has sought to emphasize bilateral contacts with the 
comecon member countries rather than bloctobloc relations this 
is mainly because the common market says comecon does not have 
equivalent authority to decide trade and other issues for its 
members 
last week the soviet union and east germany submitted formal 
requests to open their own bilateral diplomatic relations with the 
eec 
the eec hopes to wrap up a bilateral trade and cooperation 
agreement with hungary this year during their luxembourg meeting 
the foreign ministers gave the eec negotiators new instructions for 
the hungary talks 
