<DOCNO> AP880613-0275 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today barred states from 
banning all direct mail advertisements sent by lawyers to potential 
clients 
the court by a 63 vote ruled in a kentucky case that states 
violate freespeech rights when they prohibit lawyers from 
soliciting business by sending truthful and nondeceptive letters to 
people they know face particular legal problems 
writing for the court justice william j brennan said states 
may require lawyers to file copies of such soliciting letters with 
a state agency authorized to penalize actual abuses 
but brennan said the potential for abuse does not justify a 
total ban as imposed in kentucky 
our recent decisions involving commercial speech have been 
grounded in the faith that the free flow of commercial information 
is valuable enough to justify imposing on wouldbe regulators the 
costs of distinguishing the truthful from the false the helpful 
from the misleading and the harmless from the harmful brennan 
said 
he was joined by justices byron r white thurgood marshall 
harry a blackmun john paul stevens and anthony m kennedy 
the three dissenters chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices sandra day oconnor and antonin scalia said it was time 
to overturn the 1977 supreme court decision that first overturned 
the legal professions longtime ban on any type of lawyer 
advertising 
rather than continuing to work out all the consequences of 
the 1977 rulings approach we should now return to the states the 
legislative function that has so inappropriately been taken from 
them in the context of attorney advertising oconnor wrote for 
the three 
the courts 1977 decision said a total ban on lawyer advertising 
violates freespeech rights 
like other commercial speech however lawyer ads are 
constitutionally protected only when truthful and nondeceptive 
the court in 1978 expressly prohibited lawyers from seeking 
business through inperson solicitation of people known to have 
legal problems 
but today the court said that in some cases solicitation 
through direct mailings must be allowed 
admittedly a letter that is personalized to the recipient 
presents an increased risk of deception intentional or 
inadvertent brennan said but merely because targeted 
directmail solicitation presents lawyers with opportunities for 
isolated abuses or mistakes does not justify a total ban on that 
mode of protected commercial speech he added 
kentuckys total ban fashioned by the states supreme court 
follows the american bar association model rule that directmail 
solicitation be banned when a significant motive for the lawyers 
doing so is the lawyers pecuniary gain 
the aba model now declared constitutionally unsound has been 
adopted by idaho nevada north carolina washington and wyoming 
three states arizona arkansas and indiana adopted 
directmail bans more restrictive than the aba model they also now 
are likely to fall in the face of a freespeech challenge 
in kentucky the ban on targeted directmail ads was challenged 
by richard d shapero a louisville lawyer 
shapero had wanted to send a letter to potential clients against 
whom foreclosure lawsuits had been filed but he was told that 
mailing such a solicitation would violate the state lawyerethics 
rules 
shaperos case now returns to the kentucky supreme court for 
further study 
the case is shapero vs kentucky bar association 87l6 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
