<DOCNO> AP880613-0278 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed banks to use 
subsidiaries to engage in underwriting and dealing in some 
securities 
the court over two dissenting votes let stand a ruling that 
such activity does not violate a 1933 law aimed primarily at 
protecting the financial stability of banks by restricting them 
from speculating in stocks and bonds 
justices harry a blackmun and sandra day oconnor voted to hear 
arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such 
review 
the 1933 federal law the glasssteagall act was passed by 
congress in the wake of the stock market crash of 1929 
the law placed various restrictions on banks in large measure 
to protect deposits from being squandered on wall street 
in recent years the wall of separation between commercial and 
investment bank activities has been lowered 
at issue in the case acted on today were rulings by the federal 
reserve board allowing some of the nations leading banks to use 
subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in municipal revenue bonds 
mortgagerelated securities and commercial paper the latter is a 
form of iou used by corporations to finance shortterm debt 
the federal reserve board last year said bank subsidiaries may 
underwrite and deal in such securities as long as they do not 
exceed 5 to 10 percent of the subsidarys gross revenue 
the board said that is in line with the glassstegall acts 
requirement that banks may not affiliate with an organization 
engaged principally in underwriting or dealing in securities 
the boards rulings were challenged by the securities industry 
association a trade group of underwriters brokers andd securities 
dealers 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals in february upheld the 
federal reserve board decisions and the reagan administration 
urged the justices to leave intact the appeals court rulng 
justice department lawyers said the federal reserve board acted 
properly and that any change in banking regulations should be left 
to congress 
the government noted that a moratorium congress imposed on the 
type of banking activities involved in the dispute expired in 
march and congress has not renewed it moreover legislation is 
pending to repeal parts of the glasssteagall act 
reacting to todays decision edward i obrien president of 
the securities industry association said we are disappointed 
the supreme court decided not to hear our appeal to prevent banks 
through affiliates from engaging in a wide range of securities 
but we are pleased the federal reserve itself has erected a 
series of firewalls to prevent banks from taking excessive 
risks within the securities arena which would further weaken banks 
and thus endanger the nations economy obrien said 
charles pistor president of the american bankers association 
said this is another hole in the anticompetitive glasssteagall 
act and another important victory for consumers but before large 
numbers of bank customers will benefit we need to repeal the 
glasssteagall act and allow all banks to offer securities 
services 
the case is securities industry association vs federal reserve 
system 871513 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

